derscoring their contradictions. The book offers provocative new insights about Brunias’s work gleaned from a broad survey of his paintings, many of which are reproduced here for the first time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic books. 0aImperialism in art. 0aRace in art. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  a"idian trade scenes.  aAfro-Creoles.  aAgostino Brunias.  aBlack Caribs.  aBritish colonial Caribbean.  aBritish colonial art.  aCarib Wars.  aCaribbean life.  acolonial West Indians.  adark-skinned Africans.  alate-eighteenth century Britain.  amixed-race people.  apaintings.  aplantocratic elites.  avisual ethnography.1 aBagneris, Mia L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612046540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526120465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526120465/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles